sections.markdown:
### Parsing

In DQL, we can also parse any data in order to extract this into different fields or filter based on the result.

I have an example here, and an exercise for you below.

When parsing, make sure to click on the field you want to parse, in this case `content` and select `Extract Fields`. This opens the DPL architect.

DPL (Dynatrace Pattern Language) is used to extract fields.

You can parse on-demand (so parse any data you have ever captured) or as part of a Processing pipeline (e.g. to chart this into metrics for alerting). Parsing in a processing pipeline is typically the fastest, and allows you to skip complicated parses as part of queries.

Take a look at the below three parsing examples, then complete the **Parsing Exercise**.

Parse documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/extraction-and-parsing-commands

DPL documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/dpl-dynatrace-pattern-language-hub

DPL documentation for LD: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/dpl-lines-strings#line-data

sections.title: Parsing Example 1 - Find all logs containing IP Addresses

input.value:
fetch logs
| parse content, """DATA  IPADDR:ip_first """ //we can also directly match the first hit that fits the IP-address datatype. Unfortunately it's not what we were looking for!
| filter isNotNull(ip_first)

sections.markdown:
### Summarize

You might have noticed the limit of 1000 log lines in most notebooks.

When retrieving data, we only show you the first 1000 (or more/less if you specify a `limit` parameter).

Often, you don't need to read every individual log line - but if we want to answer the interesting questions, we do want DQL to read all of that.

We can achieve such things with the `summarize` command.

The summarize command consists of two parts:
* Aggregation - count(), sum(value), countIf(), or multiple of these. Use the auto-complete for suggestions!
* Splitting - we can give the total number, or split this by a certain value. We do this by using the `by:` clause.

**Exercise 1:** How many log lines have we had in the last 2 hours?

**Exercise 2:** How many log lines have we had in the last 2 hours, split by `{log.source}`?

Summarize documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/aggregation-commands#summarize

### makeTimeseries

If the data isn't in a timeseries format, e.g. log data, we can turn it into timeseries using the `makeTimeseries` command.

It requires that a timestamp field is available.

**Exercise:** Using `makeTimeseries`, chart the count of log lines over the last two hours.

**Exercise 2:** Split your query by `log.source`

MakeTimeseries documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/aggregation-commands#makeTimeseries

### Lookup

Sometimes we have data where we would like to relate it to another query.
In this case, we have a timeseries but we only have entity ID's.

**Exercise 1:** Run the below example query. Uncomment the lookup function and see how the result changes

**Exercise 2:** Write a lookup query and fill in the entityNames in the place of the entityID's. You might have to remove all fields containing entity ID's for the chart to change.

If you cannot see the Process Names after doing the lookup, try to view the `Raw` result and remove the fields containing an entity ID.

metrics.description: This metric provides the percentage of the CPU usage of a process. The metric value is the sum of CPU time every process worker uses divided by the total available CPU time. The result is expressed in percentage. A value of 100% indicates that the process uses all available CPU resources of the host. It has a "Process" dimension (dt.entity.process_group_instance).

input.value:
timeseries process_cpu = avg( dt.process.cpu.usage ), by:{dt.entity.process_group}
| lookup
